Throughout the country of Bolivia, there is still a strong reminder of a stretch of coastline lost to Chile in a bloody 19th-century conflict on resources, and so is the longing for re-sealing in the Pacific.
The hopes may be at their highest for decades, while Bolivia awaits a judgment from the International Court on 1 October after five years of voting.
"Bolivia has momentum, a sense of community and clarity, and of course waits with a positive look at the outcome," said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians will see the decision of the International Court of Justice on large screens throughout the country and hope that the Court of Justice in The Hague will agree that Chile – after decades of discussion – is obliged to negotiate to give Bolivia sovereignty over an area with access to the sea.
Evo Morales, Bolivia's charismatic indigenous president, who is facing a controversial election campaign next year, is also at stake on Monday's judgment.
"We are close to returning to the Pacific," he promised last August.
But analysts believe that it is unlikely that the court will take Bolivia’s party – and that there would be no major change if it did.
The United Nations Assembly, which sits in the Netherlands, has no power to hand over Chilean territory and has stipulated that it cannot determine the outcome of possible discussions.
The fact that the International Court of Justice gave judgment only six months after the final arguments were heard indicates that the case "was not complicated," said Paz Zárate, a Chilean expert in international law.
And instead of promoting Bolivia's case, the last four years may have given way to setbacks.
"The story of access to the sea has been hijacked by the current Bolivian leadership," Zárate said.
Morales' war rhetoric has done away with the remaining Chilean goodwill, she said.
Bolivia and Chile will continue their discussions at some point, but it will be extremely difficult to discuss after this.
The two countries have not exchanged ambassadors since 1962.
Former President Eduardo Rodríguez Veltzé, Bolivia's representative in The Hague, rejected the idea that the decision-making process of the Court was abnormally rapid.
On Monday, Bolivia will have "an extraordinary opportunity to open a new era of relations with Chile" and a chance to "end an era of 139 years with disagreements and gain benefits for both parties," he said.
Calzadilla also denied that Morales, who is still one of Latin America's most popular presidents, used the maritime problem as a political crutch.
"Bolivia will never give up access to the Pacific," he added.
"The court order is an opportunity to see that we have overcome the past."
