North Korea says they will not disarm unilaterally if there is no trust
On Saturday the Foreign Minister of North Korea told the UN that continued sanctions strengthen their mistrust of the United States and that it will not give up its nuclear weapons unilaterally under such conditions.
Ri Yong Ho told the General Assembly of the world-wide organization that North Korea had shown “significant goodwill” in the last year, for example by stopping nuclear and missile tests, settling an area for nuclear testing and promising not to further develop nuclear weapons and nuclear technology.
"However, we have not seen a similar reaction from the United States," he said.
"Without confidence in the United States, there is no confidence in our national security, and under such conditions there is no chance that we ourselves will take first steps and disarm unilaterally."
While he repeated well-known North Korean complaints about Washington's opposition to a "phase-sharing" approach to nuclear disarmament, where North Korea would be rewarded if they took gradual steps. However, his speech seemed important as it did not unequivocally reject unilateral disarmament, as otherwise had been the case with Pyongyang.
Ri referred to a joint statement by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first summit ever between a sitting American president and a North Korean leader in Singapore on 12 June, where Kim promised to work "nuclear disarmament on the Korean peninsula", while Trump promised to guarantee North Korea's security.
North Korea has requested a formal end to the Korean war, which took place in 1950-53, but the United States has said that Pyongyang must first give up their nuclear weapons.
Washington has also shown opposition to softening international sanctions against North Korea.
"The US insists on 'nuclear disarmament first' and expands the pressure with sanctions to achieve their purpose by coercion and even opposes the 'declaration of the end of the war'," said Ri.
"The perception that sanctions can bring us to our knees is a wishful dream among people who do not know who we are.
But the problem is that the continued sanctions strengthen our mistrust."
Ri did not mention any more plans for a summit between Kim and Trump, as the American leader pointed out at the UN earlier this week.
Instead, the Minister highlighted three meetings between Kim and the South Korean leader Moon Jae-in within the last five months and added: "If nuclear disarmament were to be negotiated with South Korea and not the United States, the negotiations would not be so locked."
Nevertheless, the tone of Ris speech was very different from last year when he told the UN General Assembly that firing North Korea's rockets against the mainland was inevitable, after "Mr Evil President" Trump called Kim a "rocked man" on a suicide mission.
Last year, Trump in the United Nations threatened with "total destruction" by North Korea, but this year he praised Kim to show courage in relation to disarmament, but said that there is still a lot to be done and that the sanctions have to remain until North Korea is demolished.
On Wednesday, Trump said that he did not have a timetable for these actions, but said, "It doesn't matter whether it takes two years, three years or five months."
China and Russia believe that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the steps taken.
