Harvard students take a course to get enough sleep
A new course at Harvard University has given all bachelor students more sleep. The aim of the course is to counteract the growing macho culture where you study all night held up by large amounts of caffeine.
A researcher has shown that students at the world's best university often do not know the first thing about taking care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and specialist at the Brigham and Women's Hospital, has completed the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
He got the idea for the course after giving a presentation on the effects of sleep deprivation on learning.
"When the assignment was finished, a girl came up to me and said, "Why do I get to know this only now that I'm on the candidate?"
"She said that no one had ever told her about the importance of sleep, which surprised me," he told The Telegraph.
The course, offered for the first time this year, explains how good sleep habits can improve your academic and sporting performance and your overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and managing director of the university's health care area, says that the university has decided to offer the course after finding out that the students were in serious sleep deprivation during the week.
The hourly course consists of various interactive exercises.
In one of the exercises there is a picture of a dorm where students need to click on coffee cups, curtains, running shoes and books to learn about the effects of caffeine and light, and how one’s sporty performance is affected by lack of sleep and how important good sleep habits are.
In another part of the course, participants hear about how sleep deprivation over a long period of time increases the risk of heart attacks, blood clots, depression and cancer.
Participants are encouraged to think about their daily habits by clicking on different icons on an interactive map of campus.
"We know that this will not change students' behaviour immediately.
But we think they have the right to know - just as you have the right to know how cigarettes affect your health," adds Professor Czeisler.
The pride of taking a "allnighter" still exists, he says and adds that modern technology and increased pressure on the students have led to sleep deprivation being a growing problem.
The "secret weapon" against stress, fatigue and anxiety is good and sufficient sleep, he said – it even counteracts weight gain, because lack of sleep makes the brain think that you are starving, why they are constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian who studies chemical and physical biology, helped last year Professor Czeisler organize the course when he took one of his courses at Harvard.
He said that the course had opened his eyes and made him work to make it a general course throughout the university.
He hopes that the next will be that all graduates will be offered a similar course before continuing their education.
Professor Czeisler recommends the students to set an alarm so that they know when to go to bed and when to go up. This can raise awareness of the harmful effects of the light from electronic screens, which can move at the dawn and make it harder to fall asleep.
