National Trust Snipers for the Secret Life of Bats
New research from an area in the Scottish Highlands is trying to reveal how bats use the landscape when hunting.
The hope is that the findings will shed light on the behaviour of the unique flying mammals and will help in the work on future conservation efforts.
The study is conducted by scientists from Scotland's National Trust and follows common bats, dwarf bats, long-eyed bats and aquatic bats at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recording equipment is located in carefully selected locations in the area to record the activities of bats throughout the season.
Data is also collected from staff from NTS and volunteers using handheld detectors.
In-depth analysis of the audio recordings will reveal the frequencies of the bats and show which species is doing what.
To produce a detailed landscape view of their behavior, a report and a map of their habitat are made.
NTS Rob Dewar nature conservation consultant hopes that the results reveal which areas of habitat are most important and how they are used by the different species.
This knowledge can help to determine the benefits of habitat conservation efforts such as the establishment of meadows and how best to preserve forest areas for bats and similar species.
The number of bats in Scotland and the United Kingdom has fallen dramatically over the last 100 years.
They are threatened by buildings and urban expansion projects that affect shipowners and restrict their habitat.
Windmills and lighting can also pose a danger, as can flu traps, chemical treatment of building materials and attacks by pets.
In fact, bats aren't blind.
But because they primarily hunt at night, their ears are more useful than their eyes.
They use an advanced echolocation technique to find insects and fly around obstacles.
NTS, which is responsible for the preservation of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land around the country, takes bats very seriously.
They have ten trained experts who often collect data, inspect nests and sometimes perform rescue operations.
The organization has even made Scotland's first and only dedicated bat reserve at the area around Thrave in Dumfries and Galloway, home to eight out of ten of Scotland's bat species.
The caretaker of the area, David Thompson, says it is an ideal territory for them.
"Here at Threate we have a really good area for bats," he said.
"We have old buildings, a lot of old trees and all the good habitat.
There is a lot you don't know about bats, so the work here and elsewhere can help to understand what they need to thrive."
He emphasizes the importance of looking for bats before making maintenance tasks on properties, as the destruction of a single nest can kill up to 400 females and young people, thereby risking the destruction of an entire local population.
The bats are at peace, and it is illegal to kill, harass or disturb them or their nests.
Elisabeth Ferrell, the Scottish project manager for the Bat Conservation Trust, has encouraged the public to give a hand.
She said, "We still have a lot to learn about our bats, and for many of the species we have, we don't know how the populations develop."
